{"id":"1506.05377","submitter":"Sourabh Lahiri","authors":"Sourabh Lahiri, Yang Wang, Massimiliano Esposito, David Lacoste","title":"Kinetics and thermodynamics of reversible polymerization in closed\n  systems","comments":null,"journal-ref":"New J. Phys. 17, 085008 (2015)","doi":"10.1088/1367-2630/17/8/085008","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Motivated by a recent work on the metabolism of carbohydrates in bacteria, we\nstudy the kinetics and thermodynamics of two classic models for reversible\npolymerization, one preserving the total polymer concentration and the other\none not. The chemical kinetics is described by rate equations following the\nmass-action law. We consider a closed system and nonequilibrium initial\nconditions and show that the system dynamically evolves towards equilibrium\nwhere detailed balance is satisfied. The entropy production during this process\ncan be expressed as the time derivative of a Lyapunov function. When the\nsolvent is not included in the description and the dynamics conserves the total\nconcentration of polymer, the Lyapunov function can be expressed as a\nKullback-Leibler divergence between the nonequilibrium and the equilibrium\npolymer length distribution. The same result holds true when the solvent is\nexplicitly included in the description and the solution is assumed dilute,\nwhether or not the total polymer concentration is conserved. Furthermore, in\nthis case a consistent nonequilibrium thermodynamic formulation can be\nestablished and the out-of-equilibrium thermodynamic enthalpy, entropy and free\nenergy can be identified. Such a framework is useful in complementing standard\nkinetics studies with the dynamical evolution of thermodynamic quantities\nduring polymerization.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 17 Jun 2015 16:16:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-09-30"}
